Phase 1: Target Machine Build (Dell E6230)
Objective
Install bare-metal Windows 10 Pro as an intentionally vulnerable target machine with RDP
enabled and weak credentials.
Tools Used
Microsoft Media Creation Tool
Rufus 4.14
Process
1. Create bootable Windows USB
Downloaded Windows 10 ISO via Media Creation Tool. Used Rufus 4.14 to write ISO to Lexar
32GB USB with MBR partition scheme to support Legacy BIOS on the E6230.
Key Rufus settings:
Partition scheme: MBR
Target system: BIOS or UEFI-CSM
File system: FAT32
2. Boot from USB

Accessed Dell boot menu via F12 on startup. Selected USB Storage Device.
3. Install Windows
Selected Custom installation to wipe all existing partitions. Deleted all three existing
partitions (System Reserved, Primary, OEM Reserved) leaving unallocated space. Installed
Windows 10 Pro without a product key (unactivated is acceptable for lab use).
4. Post-install configuration
Created local account: labuser with intentionally weak password (lab target)
Skipped Microsoft account
Declined all privacy data collection settings
Enabled Remote Desktop: Settings > System > Remote Desktop > On
Disabled Windows Update to preserve unpatched attack surface
Confirmed IP via ipconfig : 192.168.8.168

Phase 2: Attack Machine Build (MSI GT72VR)
Objective
Install bare-metal Kali Linux 2026.1 as the primary attack platform.
Tools Used
Rufus 4.14
Kali Linux 2026.1 Installer ISO (x86_64)
Process
1. Download Kali ISO
Downloaded Kali Linux 2026.1 Installer (x86_64) from kali.org/get-kali.
2. Create bootable USB
Used Rufus 4.14 with MBR partition scheme. Rufus prompted to download matching Grub
2.12 bootloader — selected Yes.
3. Disable Secure Boot

MSI BIOS blocked Kali with Secure Boot Violation error. Entered BIOS via Delete key on
startup. Navigated to Security tab, disabled Attempt Secure Boot. Changed Boot mode from
UEFI to Legacy to resolve NVRAM volume full error with MOK keys.
4. Install Kali
Booted from USB in Legacy/BIOS mode. Selected Graphical Install (text installer ran due to
timing but functioned identically).
Key installation decisions:
Hostname: kali
Username: kali
Partition: Guided, use entire disk on /dev/nvme0n1 (256GB Samsung NVMe)
Partition scheme: All files in one partition
Desktop: Xfce (default) with top10 and default tool collections
GRUB installed to /dev/nvme0n1
5. Post-install configuration
After first boot, configured the system:

Connected to home WiFi temporarily via nmtui to perform updates. Switched to lab
network (Home Lab 5G) post-configuration.
# Fix APT sources
echo "deb http://http.kali.org/kali kali-rolling main non-free contrib" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list
# Fix DNS
echo "nameserver 8.8.8.8" | sudo tee /etc/resolv.conf
# Lock DNS to prevent NetworkManager from overwriting
sudo chattr +i /etc/resolv.conf
# Full system update
sudo apt update && sudo apt full-upgrade -y
# Enable SSH
sudo systemctl enable ssh
sudo systemctl start ssh
# Clean up
sudo apt autoremove -y

Final IP on lab network: 192.168.8.230 (wlan0)

